[1] United Kingdom: increased incidence, low perception of risk in the population
Date: Tue 10 Jul 2018
Source: The Times [edited]
https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/dr-mark-porter-measles-is-on-the-rise-and-youre-more-likely-to-catch-it-on-holiday-njndhfhtw


General practitioners (GPs) are being urged to be vigilant for measles, particularly in people returning from European hotspots such as Italy, France, Greece, Romania and Russia. There have been nearly 600 recorded cases of measles in England alone this year [2018] -- more than throughout 2017 -- and most were caught abroad, but what are the risks? And how can travellers, adults and children protect themselves?

Risk, or rather perception of risk, is an odd thing when it comes to illnesses such as measles (and mumps and rubella/German measles). The public tend to worry too much about rare but dangerous infections and too little about common "childhood" diseases that only occasionally maim or kill. Yet, overall, the milder diseases tend to exact the biggest toll.

Most people, for instance, are more than happy to be vaccinated against tetanus (and often actively ask for it after an injury), but would not think of having the measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) jab before heading off to Russia to watch the World Cup. Yet in a typical year, there are only a handful of tetanus cases in the UK, and the milder, but much commoner, measles virus has killed twice as many people over the past 20 years.

It is not only children who are at risk from measles. Indeed, adults over 30 years of age are those most likely to develop complications. Serious problems are still comparatively rare, but pneumonia can strike in as many as one in 16 cases, about one in 1500 cases will develop encephalitis (inflammation of the brain), and at least one in 5000 will die (there were 35 deaths across Europe last year [2017]).

I have a vested interest. My youngest sister, Caroline, was born profoundly deaf after my mother caught German measles (rubella) during pregnancy, before the MMR jab was introduced. One of the many advantages of protecting people against measles is that you can also protect them against mumps and rubella. So, who should consider the MMR jab?

In theory, the vaccine is available to anyone who has not had both shots (typically given at one year of age and just before start of school). The vaccine was not introduced until the late 1980s, although separate jabs were available from the early 1970s. Your GP records should detail what you have had, and if you did not receive both doses, then you can get the vaccine free from the National Health Service (NHS).

Doctors are most interested in those who have missed out after the MMR scare in the 1990s when the vaccine was linked -- wrongly -- to autism. In particular, young women in their late teens or early twenties who will soon be considering starting a family [are at risk of not having received the vaccine]. If this sounds like you, then please talk to your GP or practice nurse about having the MMR jab before trying to conceive (you cannot have the jab while pregnant). My sister was one of the lucky ones. Rubella in pregnancy can do far more than destroy a child's hearing.

This same cohort of young adults is also most at risk while visiting Europe over the summer because they are more likely to attend crowded events such as music festivals and football matches or nightclubs, where the highly contagious virus spreads easily. However, travellers of any age should check the latest guidance for their destination on websites such as NHS Scotland's fitfortravel.nhs.uk, and if they have not had both MMR jabs to consider vaccination where advised -- even if they think they may have had measles, mumps or rubella as a child.

What about side effects? A sore arm and occasionally a mild measles- or mumps-type illness, and/or aching joints (particularly adults) are the commonest complaints, so have the jab at least one month before your trip. As many as one in 1000 children will have a febrile convulsion, and one in 24 000 develop a problem with blood clotting (due to fewer platelets), which can lead to bruising and bleeding.

Visit http://nhs.uk/conditions/vaccinations/mmr-vaccine/ for more information.

[byline: Dr Mark Porter]

