[2] France: death of a transplant recipient and athlete, questioning of antivaccine groups
Date: Thu 19 Jul 2018
Source: Tech2 [edited]
https://cnnchile.com/mundo/crece-el-debate-mundial-contra-los-antivacunas-tras-la-muerte-de-destacada-atleta-francesa_20180711/
English: https://tech2.org/chile/the-global-debate-against-anti-vaccines-grows-after-the-death-of-a-prominent-french-athlete/


The French athlete Marine Eraville died at age 16 years on Tuesday [17 Jul 2018] after a measles outbreak. The athlete faced her first health battle at 2 years of age when she received a heart transplant, which did not prevent her from later representing France in the Olympic Games for transplant [recipients]. Eraville won medals in swimming in South Africa, Argentina and Spain, Biobiochile reported.

After the death of Marine Eraville from measles, the world debate grows against antivaccine groups, whose actions contribute to the low rate of vaccination and have led to this disease advancing when it was already believed to be controlled. According to our partner associates, in south west France where this outbreak of measles occurred, there are 2 situations that keep citizens at constant risk: that of several who refuse to trust the effects of vaccination plus the crisis that some French cities experience when the coverage is not as broad as is commonly believed.

Marine's case was complicated by the fact that she was born in a home where she did not receive vaccines because of her medical condition; however, the complaint grows against those who do have the health to inoculate and who, by ideals, decide not to do so and sometimes even encourage others not to vaccinate.

The World Health Organization (WHO) warned in February [2018] that cases in the European Union increased 400 per cent in 2017.

The current debate was sparked on social networks, especially by specialized medical sites, which criticize antivaccination groups.

