[4] EU/EEA
Date: Mon 16 Jul 2018
Source: Health Europa [edited]
https://www.healtheuropa.eu/outbreaks-measles-virus-eu/87173/


The outbreak of the measles virus continues across EU/EEA countries, according to the latest Communicable Diseases Threats Report (CDTR). In a report on the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control's (ECDC) website, it says the most recent collected data through epidemic intelligence revealed the following countries have reported the highest number of measles virus cases in 2018: Romania, 4317; France, 2588; Greece, 2238; and Italy, 1716. Since the start of the year [2018], there have been 31 reported deaths across the region due to measles.

To stop transmission of measles and to protect those most vulnerable to severe complications and death, especially infants, it has been advised that at least 95 per cent of the population needs to be vaccinated with 2 doses of a vaccine comprising measles. There are only 4 EU/EEA countries that have managed to reach the 95 per cent target for both the 1st and 2nd doses, which has shown officials that more action is needed to combat this growing issue.

All 6 member states of the World Health Organization (WHO) [sic. See WHO's list of member states http://www.who.int/choice/demography/by_country/en/; and Wikipedia's entry for WHO says 194. - Mod.SH] have the objective to eliminate measles globally by 2020. The ECDC concluded in its report: "The continued circulation of measles in the region stresses the importance for people to be vaccinated with 2 doses, to protect themselves and their families."

