[4] South America (Brazil, Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Wed 11 Jul 2018
Source: MercoPress [edited]
http://es.mercopress.com/2018/07/11/cepa-de-sarampion-venezolana-ingreso-a-brasil-463-casos-confirmados-y-dos-muertes
English: https://vaaju.com/chileeng/463-confirmed-cases-and-two-deaths-mercopress/


As of 20 Jun 2018, 463 cases (200 in Roraima and 263 in the Amazon) were confirmed and 1545 investigated, the Ministry [of Health] said in a bulletin. According to laboratory investigations, the strain of the virus found in Brazil is the same strain in circulation in Venezuela, a country suffering from a strong health crisis.

Rio de Janeiro registered its 1st 2 cases of measles in 18 years, reported the Ministry of Health in Brazil after the virus was found in other regions in the country. The health body said in a statement that the patients are students at the Faculty of Law of the Federal University of Rio de Janeiro. Last week, the Ministry of Health confirmed an outbreak of measles in the states of Amazon and Roraima, in the northern part of the country, where the virus had been eradicated since 2016.

The 2 deaths from measles this year [2018] were in Roraima, a state bordering Venezuela and the main recipient of the growing flow of immigrants into the country. In addition, 2 Venezuelans died in early 2018 from the disease.

According to laboratory studies, the strain of the virus found in Brazil is the same found in Venezuela, a country suffering from a crisis with shortages of food, basic products and medications. On the other hand, according to data from the Ministry of Health as of 11 Jun 2018, 2 cases of measles among Brazilian Yanomami people in the same border area and 24 additional cases in Venezuelan domestic people were confirmed. There are still 61 cases under investigation.

The human rights organization Survival International issues a warning: "These communities are the most vulnerable. Urgent medical help is the only thing between them and devastation," says director Stephen Corry. Measles is a contagious disease, caused by an airborne virus. Red spots on the skin, fever, cough and conjunctivitis are the common symptoms.

Vaccination in Brazil is permanent and nonstationary, but the government has intensified its activities due to the recent low immunization rate and the return of disease.

--
communicated by:
Kathryn Soderholm
